{"parentUuid":"0a37c797-a530-4d30-b3e3-b012203f022e","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/workspaces/agent-feed/prod","sessionId":"892909d3-aa5f-4e15-a679-572d401e85fb","version":"1.0.120","gitBranch":"v1","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-20250514","id":"msg_0165hhC1p1CUN4EPKFJQcwvY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Mathematical Framework\n\n### Quantum Superposition Foundation\nIn quantum mechanics, particles can exist in multiple states simultaneously (superposition). For a single particle, this is represented as:\n```\n|ψ⟩ = α|0⟩ + β|1⟩\n```\nwhere α and β are complex probability amplitudes.\n\n### Entangled States\nFor two particles, an entangled state cannot be written as a simple product of individual states. The classic example is the Bell state:\n```\n|Ψ⟩ = (1/√2)(|00⟩ + |11⟩)\n```\n\nThis means the system is in a superposition where both particles are either in state 0 or both in state 1, but we cannot say which until measured."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":315,"cache_read_input_tokens":41858,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":315,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CUabDdU6WCERZXq9SjDwK","type":"assistant","uuid":"d63173b0-b139-4ce1-a7aa-9f6144439e52","timestamp":"2025-10-29T01:04:46.017Z"}
